Step 1: Calculate the Current Ratio  
• Total Current Assets (end amount) = 8,810,936.45  
• Total Current Liabilities (end amount) = 2,491,297.55  
• Current Ratio = 8,810,936.45 / 2,491,297.55 ≈ 3.54  

Step 2: Calculate the Quick Ratio  
• Inventory = 3,540,000.00  
• Quick Assets = Total Current Assets – Inventory = 8,810,936.45 – 3,540,000.00 = 5,270,936.45  
• Quick Ratio = 5,270,936.45 / 2,491,297.55 ≈ 2.12  

Step 3: Calculate the Debt to Asset Ratio  
• Total Liabilities = Total Current Liabilities = 2,491,297.55 (there are no additional liabilities provided)  
• Total Assets (end amount) = 14,089,860.66  
• Debt to Asset Ratio = 2,491,297.55 / 14,089,860.66 ≈ 0.18  

Step 4: Calculate the Debt to Equity Ratio  
• Total Owner's Equity (end amount) = 11,598,563.11  
• Debt to Equity Ratio = 2,491,297.55 / 11,598,563.11 ≈ 0.21  

Step 5: Calculate the Cash Flow to Debt Ratio  
• Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –4,398,760.38  
• Total Debt = 2,491,297.55  
• Cash Flow to Debt Ratio = –4,398,760.38 / 2,491,297.55 ≈ –1.77  

Thus, the final solution is:

    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.18",

  }
}
